1
00:01:09,610 --> 00:01:13,860
[Inaudible]

2
00:01:27,250 --> 00:01:30,290
[Gargling]

3
00:01:38,510 --> 00:01:41,260
[Man] You're live in two minutes,<br/>Your Royal Highness.

4
00:01:43,010 --> 00:01:44,600
Sir?

5
00:01:49,600 --> 00:01:50,600
Thank you.

6
00:01:54,480 --> 00:01:56,650
Let the microphone do the work, sir.

7
00:01:58,530 --> 00:02:02,700
I'm sure you'll be splendid.<br/>Just take your time.

8
00:02:05,700 --> 00:02:08,330
[Warming Up Voice Softly]

9
00:02:14,130 --> 00:02:15,170
Time to go.

10
00:02:22,850 --> 00:02:24,510
[BBC News Reader]<br/>Good afternoon.

11
00:02:24,600 --> 00:02:28,520
"This is the BBC National Program<br/>and Empire Service...

12
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:31,810
...taking you to Wembley Stadium<br/>for the closing ceremony...

13
00:02:31,900 --> 00:02:33,810
...Of the Empire Exhibition.

14
00:02:33,900 --> 00:02:36,820
...Where His Royal Highness,<br/>the Duke of York,...

15
00:02:36,900 --> 00:02:41,780
...will read a message from his father;<br/>His Majesty King George V."

16
00:02:41,870 --> 00:02:45,160
"Fifty eight British colonies<br/>and dominions have taken part,...

17
00:02:45,240 --> 00:02:49,330
making this the largest exhibition<br/>staged anywhere in the world."

18
00:02:49,410 --> 00:02:53,170
Remember, sir, three flashes,<br/>then steady red means you're live.

19
00:02:53,250 --> 00:02:55,380
[BBC News Reader]<br/>"Using the new invention of radio,...

20
00:02:55,460 --> 00:02:58,670
...the opening ceremony was the first time<br/>His Majesty the King...

21
00:02:58,760 --> 00:03:01,680
...addressed his subjects on the wireless."

22
00:03:01,760 --> 00:03:04,050
"At the close of the first season,

23
00:03:04,140 --> 00:03:07,350
...the heir to the throne,<br/>His Royal Highness, the Prince of Wales,...

24
00:03:07,430 --> 00:03:11,270
...made his first broadcast, and today,...

25
00:03:11,350 --> 00:03:14,860
...his younger brother,<br/>His Royal Highness, the Duke of York,...

26
00:03:14,940 --> 00:03:19,070
...will give his inaugural broadcast<br/>to the nation and the world."

27
00:04:03,740 --> 00:04:06,240
[Horse Whinnies]

28
00:04:23,300 --> 00:04:25,470
[Voice Echoing]<br/>I have received...

29
00:04:33,770 --> 00:04:38,110
...from His Majesty the...

30
00:04:38,190 --> 00:04:40,190
[Stammering]

31
00:04:47,950 --> 00:04:52,410
...the...

32
00:04:55,620 --> 00:04:57,580
...the King...

33
00:05:01,050 --> 00:05:03,960
[Continues Stuttering]

34
00:05:22,530 --> 00:05:27,360
[Sir Blandine Bentham] Inhale deep into your lungs,<br/>Your Royal Highness.

35
00:05:28,360 --> 00:05:31,370
Relaxes your larynx, does it not?

36
00:05:31,450 --> 00:05:36,460
Cigarette smoking calms the nerves,<br/>and gives you confidence.

37
00:05:36,540 --> 00:05:42,540
[Chuckling] Now, if Your Royal Highness<br/>would be so kind as to open your hand.

38
00:05:51,100 --> 00:05:52,260
It's Sterilized. Now..

39
00:05:52,350 --> 00:05:55,310
One, two,

40
00:05:55,390 --> 00:05:58,640
three, four,

41
00:05:58,730 --> 00:06:02,230
five, six...

42
00:06:03,270 --> 00:06:07,150
...seven. Now, if I may take the<br/>liberty, insert them into your mouth?

43
00:06:09,450 --> 00:06:12,820
Excuse me, Doctor.<br/>What is the purpose of this?

44
00:06:12,910 --> 00:06:16,200
It's the classic approach.<br/>It cured Demosthenes.

45
00:06:16,290 --> 00:06:19,370
That was in Ancient Greece...uh<br/>Has it worked since?

46
00:06:19,460 --> 00:06:25,420
[Chuckling] Now, if you would be<br/>so kind as to read.

47
00:06:25,800 --> 00:06:27,840
"A wealth of words."

48
00:06:32,050 --> 00:06:34,890
[Mumbling]

49
00:06:34,970 --> 00:06:37,600
Fight against those marbles,<br/>Your Royal Highness.

50
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:42,230
Enunciate.

51
00:06:44,690 --> 00:06:45,730
[Voice Muffled]

52
00:06:45,820 --> 00:06:49,650
A little more concentration,<br/>Your Royal Highness.

53
00:06:51,320 --> 00:06:52,530
[Choking]

54
00:06:52,620 --> 00:06:55,490
I nearly swallowed the bloody things!

55
00:06:56,200 --> 00:07:00,250
Thank you so much, Doctor.<br/>It's been most, um...

56
00:07:00,330 --> 00:07:03,040
- ...interesting.<br/>- Your Royal Highness.

57
00:07:05,170 --> 00:07:10,300
[Stuttering] Insert marbles.<br/>He can insert his own bloody marbles.

58
00:07:16,060 --> 00:07:18,680
Tick, tock. Tick, tock.

59
00:07:20,310 --> 00:07:22,850
You know you can't<br/>keep doing this, Bertie.

60
00:07:25,730 --> 00:07:28,020
- I know.<br/>- Mmm.

61
00:07:30,860 --> 00:07:33,110
Promise me...

62
00:07:34,200 --> 00:07:35,780
Promise me no more.

63
00:08:23,580 --> 00:08:26,000
[Elevator Door Closing]

64
00:08:32,380 --> 00:08:33,880
Ah!

65
00:09:03,330 --> 00:09:04,500
Hello?

66
00:09:05,250 --> 00:09:08,880
- Is anyone there?<br/>- [Man] I'm just in the loo.

67
00:09:10,090 --> 00:09:12,050
[Toilet Flushes]

68
00:09:18,970 --> 00:09:21,760
Ah, Mrs. Johnson, there you are.

69
00:09:21,850 --> 00:09:25,230
I'm sorry, I don't have a receptionist.<br/>I like to keep things simple.

70
00:09:25,310 --> 00:09:28,060
"Poor and content<br/>is rich and rich enough."

71
00:09:28,150 --> 00:09:30,940
- I'm sorry?<br/>- Shakespeare. How are you?

72
00:09:32,730 --> 00:09:35,570
- How do you do?<br/>- Oh, chuffing along.

73
00:09:35,650 --> 00:09:39,410
Um, now, this is slightly awkward,<br/>but I'm afraid you're late.

74
00:09:40,830 --> 00:09:43,910
- Yes. I'm afraid I am.<br/>- Where's Mr. Johnson?

75
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:47,040
Ah... He doesn't know I'm here.

76
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:49,370
Well, that's not a very promising start.

77
00:09:49,460 --> 00:09:55,050
No. No, look,<br/>my husband has seen everyone...

78
00:09:55,130 --> 00:09:57,760
...To no avail.<br/>I'm awfully afraid he's given up hope.

79
00:09:57,840 --> 00:10:01,260
- He hasn't seen me.<br/>- Youâ€™re awfully sure of yourself.

80
00:10:01,350 --> 00:10:03,890
Well, I'm sure of anyone<br/>who wants to be cured.

81
00:10:03,970 --> 00:10:08,060
Of course he wants to be cured.<br/>My husband is, um...

82
00:10:08,140 --> 00:10:12,060
- Well, he's required to speak publicly.<br/>- Perhaps he should change jobs?

83
00:10:12,150 --> 00:10:16,190
- He can't.<br/>- Indentured servitude?

84
00:10:16,280 --> 00:10:19,200
Something of that nature, yes.

85
00:10:19,280 --> 00:10:22,410
Well, we need to have your hubby pop by.

86
00:10:22,490 --> 00:10:25,290
Uh... Tuesday would be good.

87
00:10:25,370 --> 00:10:28,200
He can give me his personal details,<br/>I'll make a frank appraisal...

88
00:10:28,290 --> 00:10:30,870
- ...and then we'll take it from there.<br/>- Doctor, forgive me.

89
00:10:30,960 --> 00:10:34,000
Uh, I don't have a "hubby."<br/>We don't "pop."

90
00:10:34,090 --> 00:10:37,460
And nor do we ever talk about<br/>our private lives.

91
00:10:37,550 --> 00:10:39,590
No, you must come to us.

92
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:42,970
I'm sorry, Mrs. Johnson,<br/>my game, my turf, my rules.

93
00:10:43,050 --> 00:10:44,180
Mmm.

94
00:10:44,260 --> 00:10:45,970
You'll have to talk this over<br/>with your husband,

95
00:10:46,060 --> 00:10:48,430
and then you can speak to me<br/>on the telephone.

96
00:10:48,520 --> 00:10:52,100
Thank you very much for dropping by...<br/>Good afternoon.

97
00:10:55,320 --> 00:10:58,030
And what if my husband<br/>were the Duke of York?

98
00:10:58,110 --> 00:11:02,450
- The Duke of York?<br/>- Yes... The Duke of York.

99
00:11:12,750 --> 00:11:15,630
I thought the appointment<br/>was for Johnson. Forgive me, Your...

100
00:11:15,710 --> 00:11:17,840
- Royal Highness.<br/>- ...Royal Highness.

101
00:11:17,920 --> 00:11:21,260
Yes, Johnson was used during the Great<br/>War, when the Navy didn't want the enemy

102
00:11:21,340 --> 00:11:25,010
- ...to know he was aboard.<br/>- Am I...considered the enemy?

103
00:11:25,100 --> 00:11:27,850
You will be, if you remain un-obliging.

104
00:11:28,680 --> 00:11:31,430
You'll appreciate the need<br/>for absolute discretion.

105
00:11:31,520 --> 00:11:33,600
Of course.

106
00:11:33,690 --> 00:11:36,610
How did you find me,<br/>Your Royal Highness?

107
00:11:36,690 --> 00:11:39,690
The President of The Society<br/>For Speech Therapists.

108
00:11:39,780 --> 00:11:42,570
Eileen McCleod?<br/>[Laughs] She's a sport.

109
00:11:42,660 --> 00:11:44,660
Dr McCleod warned me your antipodean<br/>methods were...

110
00:11:44,740 --> 00:11:48,030
...both "unorthodox" and "controversial."

111
00:11:48,120 --> 00:11:51,830
I warned her those<br/>are not my favorite words.

112
00:11:51,910 --> 00:11:54,540
I can cure your husband.<br/>But for my method to work,...

113
00:11:54,630 --> 00:12:00,380
...I need trust and total equality, here<br/>in the safety of my consultation room.

114
00:12:01,170 --> 00:12:02,420
No exceptions.

115
00:12:04,430 --> 00:12:06,970
Oh, well then... In that case...

116
00:12:14,850 --> 00:12:16,060
When can you start?

117
00:12:19,400 --> 00:12:23,400
[Indistinct Chattering]

118
00:12:25,450 --> 00:12:29,280
- She's still sounding a bit rough, mate.<br/>- You make me drive too slowly, Dad!

119
00:12:29,370 --> 00:12:33,080
- Did you pick Mum up from bridge?<br/>- Yeah, I've hardly been out of the car.

120
00:12:33,160 --> 00:12:36,370
I had a special visitor this afternoon.

121
00:12:36,460 --> 00:12:39,340
- [Boy] May I please leave the table?<br/>- How special's special?

122
00:12:39,420 --> 00:12:42,880
No, you must stay, bored stupid, listening<br/>to your parents' inane conversation.

123
00:12:42,970 --> 00:12:44,170
- Thanks, Dad...<br/>- And Mum.

124
00:12:44,260 --> 00:12:45,550
- And Mum.<br/>- Me, too.

125
00:12:45,630 --> 00:12:49,180
- You meeting Jean?<br/>- No. Someone else.

126
00:12:50,430 --> 00:12:53,390
- Doctor? Doctor?<br/>- Hmm?

127
00:12:53,480 --> 00:12:55,230
Go and help your brother<br/>with the washing up.

128
00:12:55,310 --> 00:12:58,020
- I'm fine.<br/>- [Woman] Who is it, Lionel?

129
00:12:58,770 --> 00:13:01,400
Why bring it up<br/>if you can't talk about it?

130
00:13:02,280 --> 00:13:06,110
Myrtle, it's just a woman<br/>looking to help her husband.

131
00:13:06,200 --> 00:13:09,780
Oh, and I had a call... for an audition.

132
00:13:09,870 --> 00:13:11,830
- One of my favorites.<br/>- Aren't they all?

133
00:13:12,700 --> 00:13:14,370
It Could be a lot of fun.

134
00:13:14,460 --> 00:13:16,460
[Door Shuts]<br/>I'm sure you'll be splendid.

135
00:13:16,540 --> 00:13:19,540
In the amateur scene,<br/>they're a highly regarded group.

136
00:13:20,920 --> 00:13:22,460
From Putney.

137
00:13:22,550 --> 00:13:25,970
[Woman] No, that's all girls.<br/>Tomorrow, chapter four, "The Flight."

138
00:13:26,050 --> 00:13:28,970
[Girl] Mama,<br/>I long to know where they fly to.

139
00:13:29,050 --> 00:13:31,470
- I can't wait!<br/>- Oh, to fly away.

140
00:13:31,560 --> 00:13:33,890
Weren't they lucky?

141
00:13:33,970 --> 00:13:35,850
Now Papa, tell a story.

142
00:13:39,730 --> 00:13:43,530
Can't I be a penguin instead?<br/>[Girls Giggling]

143
00:13:44,940 --> 00:13:49,950
Well, no, I want a penguin story.

144
00:13:51,950 --> 00:13:54,870
Very quickly.<br/>[Clears Throat]

145
00:13:56,250 --> 00:14:00,000
Once there were...<br/>[Stuttering] two princesses.

146
00:14:00,080 --> 00:14:03,170
Princess Elizabeth<br/>and Princess Margaret,

147
00:14:03,250 --> 00:14:05,760
whose papa was a penguin.

148
00:14:08,220 --> 00:14:11,470
This was because he'd been<br/>turned into one by a wicked witch.

149
00:14:12,850 --> 00:14:16,270
This was very inconvenient for him<br/>because he loved...

150
00:14:18,560 --> 00:14:21,190
...to hold his princesses in his arms.

151
00:14:21,270 --> 00:14:23,940
But you can't if you're a penguin<br/>because you...

152
00:14:24,610 --> 00:14:28,860
- ...you have wings like herrings.<br/>- Herrings don't have wings.

153
00:14:28,950 --> 00:14:33,200
Penguins have wings which are...<br/>are shaped like herrings.

154
00:14:34,990 --> 00:14:40,710
And what made matters worse is that<br/>she... she sent him to the South Pole,

155
00:14:40,790 --> 00:14:43,630
which is an awfully long walk back if...

156
00:14:43,710 --> 00:14:46,000
...if you can't fly.

157
00:14:46,090 --> 00:14:49,550
So when he reached the water, he...

158
00:14:49,630 --> 00:14:51,680
...he dived in, through the depths,

159
00:14:51,760 --> 00:14:55,140
so fast that he was in<br/>Southampton Waters by lunchtime.

160
00:14:55,220 --> 00:14:59,060
And from there,<br/>he took the 2:30 to Weybridge,

161
00:14:59,140 --> 00:15:02,730
changed at Clapham Junction, asked a...

162
00:15:02,810 --> 00:15:05,230
...a passing mallard the way<br/>to Buckingham Palace,

163
00:15:05,320 --> 00:15:08,400
swam up The Thames,<br/>out through the plughole

164
00:15:08,490 --> 00:15:13,410
and gave the cook, Mama<br/>and Mrs. Whittaker quite a shock.

165
00:15:13,490 --> 00:15:16,580
Now, when the girls<br/>heard all the commotion,

166
00:15:16,660 --> 00:15:19,750
they ran to the kitchen,<br/>where they gave him a...

167
00:15:19,830 --> 00:15:22,920
...a good scrub, a mackerel and a kiss.

168
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:25,960
And as they kissed him...

169
00:15:27,090 --> 00:15:28,500
...guess what he turned into?

170
00:15:28,590 --> 00:15:32,340
- A handsome prince.<br/>- A short-tailed albatross.

171
00:15:32,430 --> 00:15:36,140
- [Disappointed] Oh.<br/>- With wings so big,

172
00:15:36,220 --> 00:15:41,430
that he could wrap them both around<br/>his two girls together.

173
00:15:41,520 --> 00:15:43,770
Now, girls. Time for bed. Come on.

174
00:15:43,850 --> 00:15:45,810
- And take those horses to the stable.<br/>- Quickly, now.

175
00:15:45,900 --> 00:15:47,980
- You have exactly a minute.<br/>- Good night.

176
00:15:48,070 --> 00:15:50,110
Feed them, brush them and to bed.

177
00:15:51,400 --> 00:15:55,370
- Will Mrs. Simpson be there?<br/>- My brother's insisting.

178
00:15:56,490 --> 00:16:01,290
- Is he serious?<br/>- About her coming to dinner?

179
00:16:01,370 --> 00:16:03,790
No. About her.

180
00:16:05,920 --> 00:16:09,340
- A married woman? He can't be.<br/>- She can.

181
00:16:10,050 --> 00:16:12,760
By the way, I think I've found<br/>someone rather interesting.

182
00:16:12,840 --> 00:16:14,380
On Harley Street. A doctor.

183
00:16:14,470 --> 00:16:16,680
Out of the question.

184
00:16:16,760 --> 00:16:20,310
I'm not having this conversation again.<br/>Mat... Matter's settled.

185
00:16:20,390 --> 00:16:22,140
Mmm. His approach<br/>seems rather different.

186
00:16:22,230 --> 00:16:24,270
[Indistinct Whispering]

187
00:16:25,400 --> 00:16:26,400
Now?

188
00:16:27,980 --> 00:16:29,400
Now.

189
00:16:36,740 --> 00:16:39,280
Now is the winter of our discontent,

190
00:16:39,370 --> 00:16:44,160
made glorious summer<br/>by this sun of York.

191
00:16:44,250 --> 00:16:46,960
And all the clouds<br/>that lour'd upon our house

192
00:16:47,040 --> 00:16:49,670
In the deep bosom of the ocean buried.

193
00:16:49,750 --> 00:16:53,970
Now are our brows bound<br/>with... victorious... wreaths;

194
00:16:54,050 --> 00:16:55,760
Thank you.

195
00:16:58,510 --> 00:17:02,520
- Lovely diction, Mr...?<br/>- Logue. Lionel Logue.

196
00:17:02,600 --> 00:17:05,230
Well, Mr. Logue,

197
00:17:05,310 --> 00:17:09,190
I'm not hearing the cries<br/>of a deformed creature

198
00:17:09,270 --> 00:17:11,900
yearning to be king.

199
00:17:11,980 --> 00:17:16,530
Nor did I realize Richard III<br/>was King of the Colonies.

200
00:17:19,620 --> 00:17:23,240
I do know all the lines.<br/>I've played the role before.

201
00:17:23,330 --> 00:17:25,040
- Sydney?<br/>- Perth.

202
00:17:25,120 --> 00:17:27,290
Major theater town, is it?

203
00:17:27,370 --> 00:17:30,330
- Enthusiastic.<br/>- Ah.

204
00:17:30,420 --> 00:17:33,170
I was well reviewed.

205
00:17:34,550 --> 00:17:36,220
Yes.

206
00:17:36,300 --> 00:17:42,310
Well, Lionel,<br/>I think our dramatic society

207
00:17:42,390 --> 00:17:45,520
is looking for someone slightly younger.

208
00:17:45,600 --> 00:17:51,060
And a... little more regal.

209
00:17:54,230 --> 00:17:57,320
- There you are.<br/>- Thank you.

210
00:18:01,280 --> 00:18:02,240
- Oh.<br/>- Mmm.

211
00:18:02,330 --> 00:18:04,660
No, you have to shut that one first.

212
00:18:04,750 --> 00:18:07,790
Close that one first. That's it.

213
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:11,830
Where did you find this... physician?

214
00:18:11,920 --> 00:18:15,670
Classifieds. Next to a<br/>"French model, Shepherd's Market."

215
00:18:15,760 --> 00:18:17,260
No, he comes highly recommended.

216
00:18:17,340 --> 00:18:19,550
Charges substantial fees<br/>to help the poor.

217
00:18:19,890 --> 00:18:22,550
Oh, dear. Perhaps he's a Bolshevik.

218
00:18:25,100 --> 00:18:28,600
Ah, there's no receptionist.<br/>Likes to keep things simple.

219
00:18:30,730 --> 00:18:34,190
Uh... The Johnsons.

220
00:18:45,080 --> 00:18:48,620
You can go in now, Mr. Johnson.

221
00:18:48,710 --> 00:18:53,420
Lionel says wait here<br/>if you wish, Mrs. Johnson.

222
00:18:53,500 --> 00:18:56,590
Or, it being a...

223
00:18:58,300 --> 00:19:00,800
[Stuttering]<br/>... pleasant day...

224
00:19:04,260 --> 00:19:07,270
P...perhaps take a stroll.

225
00:19:08,180 --> 00:19:11,730
Was that all right, Lionel?

226
00:19:14,060 --> 00:19:15,730
Marvelous, Willie.

227
00:19:15,820 --> 00:19:18,110
You can stay here and wait for your mum.

228
00:19:19,110 --> 00:19:20,360
Mrs. Johnson.

229
00:19:21,780 --> 00:19:24,320
Mr. Johnson. Do come in.

230
00:19:43,470 --> 00:19:44,680
Would you like a sweetie?

231
00:19:44,760 --> 00:19:47,180
He's a good lad, Willie.

232
00:19:47,260 --> 00:19:50,560
He could hardly make a sound, you know,<br/>when he first came to me.

233
00:19:59,280 --> 00:20:01,860
My boys make those.<br/>They're good, aren't they?

234
00:20:03,110 --> 00:20:05,280
Please, make yourself comfortable.

235
00:20:21,510 --> 00:20:24,260
I was told not to sit too close.

236
00:20:31,980 --> 00:20:33,520
Well I believe when speaking with a prince,

237
00:20:33,600 --> 00:20:36,520
One waits for the prince<br/>to choose the topic.

238
00:20:36,610 --> 00:20:39,110
[Stuttering]

239
00:20:42,650 --> 00:20:44,570
Waiting for me to...

240
00:20:46,660 --> 00:20:50,830
...commence a conversation,<br/>one can wait rather a long wait.

241
00:20:50,910 --> 00:20:53,830
Ah, yes, well...

242
00:20:59,630 --> 00:21:01,250
Do you know any jokes?

243
00:21:08,180 --> 00:21:13,770
- Timing isn't my strong suit.<br/>- [Chuckles] Cup of tea?

244
00:21:13,850 --> 00:21:18,060
- No. No, thank you.<br/>- I think I'll have one.

245
00:21:27,570 --> 00:21:30,950
[Lionel Humming]

246
00:21:31,030 --> 00:21:33,700
Aren't you going to start treating me,<br/>Dr. Logue?

247
00:21:33,790 --> 00:21:36,830
Only if you're interested<br/>in being treated.

248
00:21:36,920 --> 00:21:40,580
Please, call me Lionel.

249
00:21:40,670 --> 00:21:43,920
No, I... prefer Doctor.

250
00:21:44,010 --> 00:21:46,550
I prefer Lionel.

251
00:21:47,720 --> 00:21:51,140
- What will I call you?<br/>- Your Royal Highness.

252
00:21:51,930 --> 00:21:54,890
Then... it's "sir" after that.

253
00:21:54,980 --> 00:21:58,810
It's a little bit formal for here.<br/>I prefer names.

254
00:21:58,900 --> 00:22:03,940
Prince Albert Frederick Arthur...

255
00:22:04,030 --> 00:22:05,110
...George?

256
00:22:05,610 --> 00:22:07,110
How about Bertie?

257
00:22:10,320 --> 00:22:13,490
- Only my family uses that.<br/>- Perfect.

258
00:22:13,580 --> 00:22:17,080
In here, it's better if we're equals.

259
00:22:20,630 --> 00:22:25,800
If... if we were equals,<br/>I wouldn't be here.

260
00:22:25,880 --> 00:22:30,760
I'd be... at home with my wife,

261
00:22:30,840 --> 00:22:32,970
and no one would give a damn.

262
00:22:33,060 --> 00:22:35,180
Please, don't do that.

263
00:22:35,270 --> 00:22:36,680
I'm sorry?

264
00:22:36,770 --> 00:22:40,850
I believe sucking smoke into your lungs,<br/>well, it will kill you.

265
00:22:40,940 --> 00:22:44,440
My physicians say it relaxes the...

266
00:22:44,520 --> 00:22:46,400
- ...the throat.<br/>- They're idiots.

267
00:22:46,490 --> 00:22:50,490
- They've all been knighted.<br/>- Makes it official, then.

268
00:22:52,620 --> 00:22:54,740
My castle, my rules.

269
00:22:58,790 --> 00:23:00,250
Thank you.

270
00:23:01,790 --> 00:23:03,380
What was your earliest memory?

271
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:07,710
- What on earth do you mean?<br/>- Your first recollection.

272
00:23:07,800 --> 00:23:09,300
I'm not...

273
00:23:12,050 --> 00:23:14,010
...here to discuss personal matters.

274
00:23:14,100 --> 00:23:17,640
- Well, why are you here, then?<br/>- Because I bloody well stammer!

275
00:23:18,600 --> 00:23:22,730
- You have a bit of a temper.<br/>- One of my many faults.

276
00:23:23,480 --> 00:23:26,690
- When did the defect start?<br/>- I've always been this way.

277
00:23:26,780 --> 00:23:28,940
- I doubt that.<br/>- Don't...

278
00:23:29,570 --> 00:23:32,070
- ...tell me, it's my stammer.<br/>- It's my field.

279
00:23:32,160 --> 00:23:36,160
I can assure you, no infant<br/>starts to speak with a stammer.

280
00:23:36,240 --> 00:23:38,240
When did yours start?

281
00:23:40,330 --> 00:23:43,370
- Four or five.<br/>- That's typical.

282
00:23:43,460 --> 00:23:46,380
So I've been told.

283
00:23:46,460 --> 00:23:49,050
I... I can't remember not doing it.

284
00:23:49,130 --> 00:23:52,760
I can believe that.<br/>Do you hesitate when you think?

285
00:23:52,840 --> 00:23:57,180
- Don't be ridiculous.<br/>- How about when you talk to yourself?

286
00:23:58,810 --> 00:24:01,350
Everyone natters to themselves<br/>occasionally, Bertie.

287
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:03,270
Stop... Stop calling me that.

288
00:24:03,350 --> 00:24:04,730
I'm not going to call you anything else.

289
00:24:04,810 --> 00:24:09,690
Then we shan't speak.<br/>[Water Boiling]

290
00:24:17,530 --> 00:24:19,160
[Blows Out Flame]

291
00:24:21,580 --> 00:24:23,910
Are you charging for this, Doctor?

292
00:24:26,540 --> 00:24:28,130
A fortune.

293
00:24:29,210 --> 00:24:31,630
[Lionel Whistling]

294
00:24:34,380 --> 00:24:36,340
I'll just let that brew.

295
00:24:37,350 --> 00:24:41,720
So... when you talk to yourself,<br/>do you stammer?

296
00:24:41,810 --> 00:24:45,480
No... of course not.

297
00:24:46,230 --> 00:24:49,980
Well, that proves that your impediment<br/>isn't a permanent part of you.

298
00:24:50,070 --> 00:24:52,320
What do you think was the cause?

299
00:24:52,400 --> 00:24:54,400
I don't... don't know.

300
00:24:54,490 --> 00:24:57,950
I... I don't... I don't care.

301
00:24:58,740 --> 00:25:00,700
I... I stammer.

302
00:25:02,750 --> 00:25:04,000
No one can fix it.

303
00:25:04,080 --> 00:25:08,710
I'll bet you that you can read<br/>flawlessly, right here, right now.

304
00:25:08,790 --> 00:25:11,920
And if I win the bet,<br/>I get to ask you more questions.

305
00:25:12,010 --> 00:25:14,920
- And if I win?<br/>- You don't have to answer them.

306
00:25:15,010 --> 00:25:19,640
One usually... wagers money.

307
00:25:19,720 --> 00:25:22,100
A bob each to keep it sweet?

308
00:25:22,180 --> 00:25:27,270
- Let's see your shilling.<br/>- I don't... carry money.

309
00:25:27,350 --> 00:25:29,810
I had a funny feeling you mightn't.

310
00:25:29,900 --> 00:25:33,360
I'll stake you, and you can<br/>pay me back next time.

311
00:25:33,440 --> 00:25:37,450
- If there is a next time.<br/>- I haven't agreed to take you on yet.

312
00:25:41,120 --> 00:25:43,990
So please stand, uh,<br/>and take a look at that.

313
00:25:44,080 --> 00:25:46,290
From there.

314
00:25:50,630 --> 00:25:54,050
I... I can't read this.

315
00:25:54,130 --> 00:25:56,630
Well, then you owe me<br/>a shilling for not trying.

316
00:26:01,930 --> 00:26:02,930
[Stutters]

317
00:26:09,310 --> 00:26:10,980
To be...

318
00:26:12,110 --> 00:26:14,320
...or not to be, that...

319
00:26:18,450 --> 00:26:23,330
- Can't read it.<br/>- Uh-uh-uh! I haven't finished yet.

320
00:26:32,500 --> 00:26:36,840
I'm going to record your voice and then<br/>play it back to you on the same machine.

321
00:26:36,920 --> 00:26:40,180
This is brilliant.<br/>It's the latest thing from America.

322
00:26:40,260 --> 00:26:41,720
It's a Silvertone.

323
00:26:54,230 --> 00:26:55,230
Pop these on.

324
00:26:57,490 --> 00:27:00,320
There's a bob in this, mate.<br/>You could go home rich.

325
00:27:08,040 --> 00:27:09,500
[  Classical Music Playing  ]

326
00:27:09,580 --> 00:27:12,580
- You're playing music!<br/>- I know.

327
00:27:12,670 --> 00:27:14,290
So how can I hear what I'm saying?

328
00:27:14,380 --> 00:27:17,960
Well, surely a prince's brain<br/>knows what its mouth's doing?

329
00:27:18,050 --> 00:27:22,470
You're not... well acquainted<br/>with royal princes, are you?

330
00:27:23,300 --> 00:27:25,720
[  Music Plays Loudly  ]

331
00:27:32,400 --> 00:27:35,230
[Voice Muffled]

332
00:27:58,340 --> 00:27:59,880
Hopeless.

333
00:27:59,960 --> 00:28:01,130
Hopeless!

334
00:28:03,720 --> 00:28:05,010
You were sublime.

335
00:28:06,390 --> 00:28:09,180
Would I lie to a prince of the realm<br/>to win 12 pennies?

336
00:28:09,270 --> 00:28:10,720
I've no idea...

337
00:28:11,270 --> 00:28:13,850
...what an Australian<br/>might do for that sort of money.

338
00:28:13,940 --> 00:28:15,940
Let me play it back to you.

339
00:28:17,230 --> 00:28:18,270
No.

340
00:28:18,360 --> 00:28:20,530
All right, then, well,<br/>I get to ask you the questions.

341
00:28:20,610 --> 00:28:24,070
Thank you, Doctor. I don't...

342
00:28:24,160 --> 00:28:26,160
...feel this is for me.

343
00:28:30,370 --> 00:28:32,200
Thank you for your time.

344
00:28:33,620 --> 00:28:35,170
Goodbye.

345
00:28:36,460 --> 00:28:37,840
Sir?

346
00:28:43,470 --> 00:28:47,760
The recording is free.<br/>Please keep it as a souvenir.

347
00:29:01,530 --> 00:29:02,940
No.

348
00:29:08,530 --> 00:29:10,080
Oh, well.

349
00:29:13,620 --> 00:29:15,370
[Whispering]<br/>Bugger.

350
00:29:19,750 --> 00:29:23,840
[George V] For the present, the work<br/>to which we are all equally bound,

351
00:29:23,920 --> 00:29:28,180
is to arrive at a reasoned tranquility<br/>within our borders,

352
00:29:28,260 --> 00:29:32,510
...to regain prosperity<br/>at this time of depression

353
00:29:32,600 --> 00:29:35,770
without self-seeking,<br/>and to carry with us

354
00:29:35,850 --> 00:29:38,980
those whom the burden of the past years

355
00:29:39,060 --> 00:29:42,190
has disheartened or overborne.

356
00:29:42,280 --> 00:29:47,740
To all, to each,<br/>I wish a happy Christmas.

357
00:29:47,820 --> 00:29:49,870
God bless you.

358
00:29:51,580 --> 00:29:53,370
[Man]<br/>And off air.

359
00:29:56,460 --> 00:29:58,120
Easy when you know how.

360
00:29:58,210 --> 00:30:00,170
[Man #2]<br/>Sir?

361
00:30:08,130 --> 00:30:09,760
Have a go yourself.

362
00:30:09,840 --> 00:30:12,050
- [Man] Congratulations, sir.<br/>- [George V] Ah, Mr. Wood.

363
00:30:12,140 --> 00:30:15,640
Splendid fellow.<br/>Chap who taught me everything I know.

364
00:30:15,730 --> 00:30:18,980
- Let the microphone do the work.<br/>- Sir.

365
00:30:19,060 --> 00:30:21,480
- Thank you.<br/>- Gentlemen.

366
00:30:21,560 --> 00:30:23,570
Sit up. Straight back.

367
00:30:23,650 --> 00:30:26,780
Face boldly up to the bloody thing<br/>and stare it square in the eye,

368
00:30:26,860 --> 00:30:29,990
as would any decent Englishman.<br/>Show who's in command.

369
00:30:30,070 --> 00:30:33,660
Papa, I d...don't... thu...thu...<br/>think I c... c... can read this.

370
00:30:33,740 --> 00:30:37,160
This devilish device will change<br/>everything if you don't.

371
00:30:37,250 --> 00:30:40,670
In the past, all a king had to do<br/>was look respectable in uniform

372
00:30:40,750 --> 00:30:42,630
and not fall off his horse.

373
00:30:42,710 --> 00:30:46,340
Now, we must invade people's homes<br/>and ingratiate ourselves with them.

374
00:30:46,420 --> 00:30:51,010
This family's been reduced to those<br/>lowest, basest of all creatures.

375
00:30:51,090 --> 00:30:52,850
We've become actors.

376
00:30:53,810 --> 00:30:55,970
We're not a family, we're a firm.

377
00:30:56,060 --> 00:30:59,020
Yet at any moment,<br/>some of us may be out of work.

378
00:30:59,100 --> 00:31:02,020
Your darling brother and future king,

379
00:31:02,110 --> 00:31:05,820
the only wife he appears interested in<br/>is invariably the wife of another.

380
00:31:05,900 --> 00:31:09,860
- He's broken off with Lady Furness.<br/>- And taken up with Mrs. Simpson.

381
00:31:09,950 --> 00:31:13,370
A woman with two husbands living.<br/>I told him straight.

382
00:31:13,450 --> 00:31:16,990
No divorced person<br/>can ever be received at court.

383
00:31:17,080 --> 00:31:22,040
He said it made him sublimely happy.<br/>[Scoffs]

384
00:31:22,130 --> 00:31:25,840
I imagine that was<br/>because she was sleeping with him.

385
00:31:25,920 --> 00:31:27,710
"I give you my word,"<br/>this is what he said.

386
00:31:27,800 --> 00:31:32,340
"I give you my word,<br/>we've never had immoral relations."

387
00:31:32,430 --> 00:31:36,510
Stared square into<br/>his father's face and lied.

388
00:31:36,600 --> 00:31:38,850
When I'm dead,<br/>that boy will ruin himself,

389
00:31:38,930 --> 00:31:41,230
this family and this nation<br/>within 12 months.

390
00:31:41,310 --> 00:31:45,730
Who will pick up the pieces, hmm?<br/>Herr Hitler intimidating half of Europe.

391
00:31:45,820 --> 00:31:48,070
Marshal Stalin the other half.

392
00:31:48,150 --> 00:31:50,440
Who will stand between us,

393
00:31:50,530 --> 00:31:54,570
the jackboots<br/>and the proletarian abyss?

394
00:31:55,580 --> 00:31:57,120
You?

395
00:31:58,540 --> 00:32:01,580
[Sighs]<br/>Well?

396
00:32:01,660 --> 00:32:04,250
With your older brother<br/>shirking his duties,

397
00:32:04,330 --> 00:32:06,840
you're going to have to do<br/>a lot more of this.

398
00:32:08,170 --> 00:32:09,710
Have a go yourself.

399
00:32:15,600 --> 00:32:18,430
Through the...<br/>[Stuttering]

400
00:32:18,510 --> 00:32:20,390
...wireless...<br/>- Get it out, boy.

401
00:32:20,480 --> 00:32:22,850
...one of the...

402
00:32:22,940 --> 00:32:24,690
... m... marvels of m...

403
00:32:26,360 --> 00:32:31,400
"Modern." Just take your time.<br/>Form your words carefully.

404
00:32:31,490 --> 00:32:33,240
...science...

405
00:32:34,200 --> 00:32:36,910
...I am enabled, this ...

406
00:32:36,990 --> 00:32:38,700
Relax.

407
00:32:42,040 --> 00:32:43,250
Just try it!

408
00:32:43,330 --> 00:32:45,210
...this Christmas Day...

409
00:32:47,710 --> 00:32:49,840
...to speak to all my...

410
00:32:51,210 --> 00:32:52,170
Do it!

411
00:32:52,260 --> 00:32:55,050
[  Ambrose and His Orchestra -<br/>Who's Been Polishing the Sun?  ]

412
00:33:06,310 --> 00:33:09,560
Lying... bastard.

413
00:33:20,410 --> 00:33:22,080
[Needle Scratches On Record]

414
00:33:28,250 --> 00:33:31,210
- [Bertie] You're playing music.<br/>- [Lionel] I know.

415
00:33:31,300 --> 00:33:34,210
[Bertie] So how can I...<br/>hear what I'm saying?

416
00:33:34,300 --> 00:33:37,550
[Lionel] Well, surely a prince's brain<br/>knows what its mouth's doing.

417
00:33:37,640 --> 00:33:41,600
[Bertie] You're not... well acquainted<br/>with royal princes, are you?

418
00:33:50,690 --> 00:33:54,820
"To be or not be,<br/>that is the question.

419
00:33:54,900 --> 00:33:57,860
Whether tis nobler in the mind to suffer

420
00:33:57,950 --> 00:34:01,370
the slings and arrows<br/>of outrageous fortune,

421
00:34:01,450 --> 00:34:04,330
or to take arms<br/>against a sea of troubles,

422
00:34:04,410 --> 00:34:07,710
and by opposing end them?

423
00:34:07,790 --> 00:34:10,920
To die, to sleep no more,

424
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:13,880
and by a sleep to say the end

425
00:34:13,960 --> 00:34:17,050
is the heartache<br/>and the thousand natural shocks

426
00:34:17,130 --> 00:34:22,760
the flesh is heir to.<br/>Tis a consummation hopeless."

427
00:34:23,390 --> 00:34:24,720
Hopeless!

428
00:34:25,680 --> 00:34:28,230
Strictly business. No...

429
00:34:30,480 --> 00:34:33,270
- ...personal nonsense.<br/>- Yes, I thought I'd made that clear...

430
00:34:33,360 --> 00:34:36,070
- ...in our interview.<br/>- Have you got the shilling you owe me?

431
00:34:36,150 --> 00:34:39,650
- No, I haven't.<br/>- Didn't think so.

432
00:34:39,740 --> 00:34:42,410
Besides, you... you tricked me.

433
00:34:42,490 --> 00:34:45,080
Physical exercises<br/>and tricks are important,

434
00:34:45,160 --> 00:34:48,410
but what you're asking will only deal<br/>with the surface of the problem.

435
00:34:48,500 --> 00:34:50,580
Is that sufficient? Uh, no.

436
00:34:50,670 --> 00:34:56,510
As far as I see it, my husband has<br/>mechanical difficulties with his speech.

437
00:34:56,590 --> 00:34:59,420
- I...<br/>- Maybe just deal with that.

438
00:35:00,430 --> 00:35:02,640
I...

439
00:35:02,720 --> 00:35:07,180
- I'm willing to work hard, Dr. Logue.<br/>- Lionel.

440
00:35:07,270 --> 00:35:11,940
[Stammering] Are you...<br/>Are you willing to do your part?

441
00:35:14,570 --> 00:35:17,280
All right. You want mechanics?

442
00:35:17,360 --> 00:35:20,530
We need to relax your jaw muscles,<br/>strengthen your tongue,

443
00:35:20,610 --> 00:35:24,320
by repeating tongue twisters.<br/>For example, "I'm a thistle-sifter.

444
00:35:24,410 --> 00:35:27,290
I have a sieve of sifted thistles<br/>and a sieve of unsifted thistles.

445
00:35:27,370 --> 00:35:29,790
- Because I am a thistle-sifter."<br/>- Fine.

446
00:35:29,870 --> 00:35:32,960
And you do have a flabby tummy,<br/>so we'll need to spend some time

447
00:35:33,040 --> 00:35:35,750
strengthening your diaphragm.<br/>Simple mechanics.

448
00:35:35,840 --> 00:35:38,050
- That's all we ask.<br/>- All that's about a shilling's worth.

449
00:35:38,130 --> 00:35:40,470
Forget about the blessed shilling!

450
00:35:53,860 --> 00:35:56,900
Perhaps, upon occasions...

451
00:35:56,980 --> 00:35:59,400
...you might be requested to assist...

452
00:36:02,490 --> 00:36:06,160
...in coping with...

453
00:36:06,240 --> 00:36:09,790
...with some minor event.<br/>Would that be agreeable?

454
00:36:09,870 --> 00:36:11,830
Of course.

455
00:36:11,910 --> 00:36:15,580
Yes, and that would be the full extent<br/>of your services.

456
00:36:15,670 --> 00:36:19,670
- Shall I see you next week?<br/>- I shall see you every day.

457
00:36:19,760 --> 00:36:24,220
[Both Vocalizing]<br/>Ahahahahhahahahahahahahahahahahah.

458
00:36:24,300 --> 00:36:26,600
Feel the looseness of the jaw.

459
00:36:26,680 --> 00:36:29,680
[Vocalizing Continues]

460
00:36:29,770 --> 00:36:31,730
Good. Little bounces. Bounces.

461
00:36:31,810 --> 00:36:33,690
Shoulders loose, shoulders loose.

462
00:36:33,770 --> 00:36:36,940
Beautiful, beautiful, beautiful.<br/>Now, loose.

463
00:36:41,150 --> 00:36:44,360
[Lionel] Take a nice deep breath.<br/>Expand the chest.

464
00:36:44,450 --> 00:36:46,450
Put your hands onto your ribs.

465
00:36:47,490 --> 00:36:49,660
Deeper. Good.

466
00:36:49,740 --> 00:36:52,790
- How do you feel?<br/>- Full of hot air.

467
00:36:52,870 --> 00:36:55,250
Isn't that what<br/>public speaking's all about?

468
00:36:55,330 --> 00:37:00,840
My wife and I are glad<br/>to visit this important...

469
00:37:00,920 --> 00:37:04,800
[Lionel] Take a good deep breath,<br/>and up comes Your Royal Highness.

470
00:37:04,880 --> 00:37:09,220
And slowly exhale,<br/>and down comes Your Royal Highness.

471
00:37:09,310 --> 00:37:11,510
- You all right, Bertie?<br/>- [Groaning] Yes.

472
00:37:11,600 --> 00:37:13,140
It's actually quite good fun.

473
00:37:13,600 --> 00:37:14,940
Mmm... Mother.

474
00:37:15,020 --> 00:37:16,650
[Lionel]<br/>Shorten the humming each time.

475
00:37:16,730 --> 00:37:18,900
Mother. Mmm...

476
00:37:18,980 --> 00:37:22,400
...manufacturing district...<br/>- [Lionel] Another deep breath.

477
00:37:22,490 --> 00:37:25,070
- And Jack and Jill.<br/>- [Bertie] Jack and Jill.

478
00:37:25,150 --> 00:37:26,990
- [Lionel] Went up the hill.<br/>- Went up the hill.

479
00:37:27,070 --> 00:37:28,740
Now, just sway.

480
00:37:29,740 --> 00:37:31,240
Perfect.

481
00:37:31,330 --> 00:37:35,120
...will not permit us to...<br/>- [Lionel] Loosen the shoulders.

482
00:37:35,210 --> 00:37:37,580
[Bertie] Ding dong bell,<br/>pussy's in the well.

483
00:37:37,670 --> 00:37:41,340
Who put her in? Little Tommy Tin.

